Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_380
Response Text: When an arts organization that might be made up of white people, or that primarily faces white people, tells the City that they are making efforts to diversify their audiences, board, etc. you should listen to them in good faith and not punish them by denying funding simply because they aren't primarily BIPoC-led or serving/facing. Plenty of more traditional (i.e., "white") organizations are making great efforts to reach underserved demographics and were making great progress until the City completely pulled the rug out from under them/us. It's really difficult for us to entice BIPoC prospective audience members to trek back into the city on a weekend (after probably doing it daily M–F) to partake of arts offerings. The cost of living crisis—which the City has, in many of our minds, done little to alleviate—has pushed BIPoC Austinites into further and further outlying communities and we can't exactly feel surprised when a Black family that has been forced to move to Bastrop or an Hispanic family that now lives in Buda or Kyle doesn't feel particularly inclined to deal with the never-ending construction and traffic to come into Austin to a concert, play, or whatever. Many orgs are doing the best they can to bring a wider range of people together, but when you force them out of business or force them to drastically cut back their offerings by shutting them out of cultural arts funding, you end up making your stated goal that much difficult for all of us.

